AGI -&nbsp;"The interpretation is the essence of jurisdiction. Without adequate guarantees of freedom of interpretation, no order can be democratic. The Italian judiciary undertakes every day to practice and to respect the constitutional principle which the judge wants subject only to the law and which constitutes the precondition for the autonomy and independence of the jurisdiction". Thus begins the final motion approved by the National Association of Magistrates, final act of the 36th Congress held in Palermo.<br> <br> IPERTROFIA SCADIMENTO E 'BUCHI' NORMATIVI<br> The Italian judiciary "publicly denounces the condition of normative hypertrophy in which it is to operate and the qualitative displacement of the normative production, more and more often imprinted to the solution of the contingent, without an adequate effort of systematic coherence". As it denounces "the persistent absence of a clear and punctual discipline on important areas that deeply touch the lives of citizens." The jurisdiction "will never succumb to the duty to answer to the question of justice formulated by citizens, even by interpreting the apories of the regulatory framework, inspired by prudence and measure in exercising its discretion, but it asks for the same sense of responsibility to be assumed by the other powers of the State in responding to the expectations of citizens". The Italian judiciary also confirms "its commitment to ensure that the answer to the question of justice is more and more timely, but the principle must be maintained that the activity of judging can never be called upon to artificial intelligence, which can and must serve to ensure more effective tools of organization, not to plead for the task of judging, which is and must remain exclusively human prerogative".
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
INTERPRETATION AND IMPARCIALITY The theme of freedom of interpretation "is intimately connected with that of the impartiality of the magistrate. Of the wide discretion immanent to the interpretative activity, the Italian magistrates give daily account to the people, in whose name they administer justice, with the motivations of their measures, which constitute the heart of the judicial activity". The dialectic between the powers draws food from criticism, which can and must also have judiciary measures, "but it must be reiterated that this criticism must move from mutual respect, be inspired by continence and be always motivated and reasoned, in the interest of the State and the trust that all citizens must put in democratic institutions. It is detrimental to the institutions a criticism that does not start from the motivations of the judiciary, and that it is founded on the research in the private life of the magistrate, of statements or mere behaviors that, sometimes misunderstood and communicated to art, can give, to the public opinion, the impression of a prejudice, of a partisanity that guided the pen". This way of making criticism of the judges' decisions "was strongly opposed, because it pollutes the public debate around justice and generates distrust towards the judiciary". Participation in the public discourse, "although with the caution imposed by the role, can contribute to a more conscious consideration of the implications of the choices that the political decision maker intends to take, especially when possible compressions of fundamental rights are highlighted, in the perspective of the pursuit of the purposes provided for in the Constitution". &nbsp;
&nbsp;
&nbsp; The Italian judiciary "conquered a patrimony of credibility and trust among citizens, also paying a price of blood among the highest in the world, and is aware that it must be defended in the daily life even with the conduct of individuals, because it is an invaluable social capital". For this reason, we must ask ourselves what themes, methods and content are most suitable for preventing instrumentalization and to prevent our voices from being confused with the basic noise of a debate, often confused and unplanned, and end up in generating even more confusion and disorientation in citizens." Among the themes, "certainly" those related to the function, role and attributes of the judiciary, "as well as those related to the substantive and procedural laws governing its work, including those defining, increasing or restricting the rights catalog. Nor can the themes which, being relevant to the balance between the powers defined by the Constitution, affect, even indirectly, the role of jurisdiction over other public powers." Thus, "the importance of the participation of all magistrates in public debate, not only as citizens with equal rights to others, but also as bearers of experience, culture, principles, inspired by constitutional values and legality". As for the reforms, Anm reiterates "its intransigent opposition to the separation of careers and the overall weakening of the Csm which constitute its main content". The uniqueness of the judiciary "is the foundational value of our associationism: This ontological feature is incompatible with any possibility of mediation and negotiation on the specific content of reforms." The separation of careers "is not at all functional to guarantee the court's terticity, but rather appears as a tool to substantially weaken the role of the prosecutor and, consequently, the function of legality control placed on the judge and lets it be felt as a tool of retaliation and threat to the judiciary all".&nbsp;
&nbsp;
&nbsp;Separate the public prosecutor from the judge, would lead to the establishment of a professional figure of 'persecutor', far from the current organ of the prosecution, which today is responsible for the search for the truth and is guarantor of respect for the prerogatives of the investigation, even in the phase of the collection of evidence by the judicial police". To separate the public prosecutor from the judge "would have very serious repercussions on the compulsory exercise of the criminal action indispensable for the implementation of the principle of equality of the citizen before the law. To the logic of separation the Am wants to counteract the logic of sharing. The cultural matrix of jurisdiction must be closely shared between judges, lawyers and prosecutors."<br> <br> A CSM MORE DEBOLE<br> The Csm "is the only presidium placed by the Constitution to protect the autonomy and independence of judiciary, which is indispensable for achieving equality of citizens in the face of the law. The reforms envisaged would fatally weaken the self-government organ of the magistrates, reducing its powers, eliminating the most important ones, compromising its authority and altering the proportion between lay and togated components. This weakening prejudices the implementation of the formal and substantial equality of citizens.' &nbsp;
&nbsp;

